<li id="cite_note-Keegan_1997_35-65"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Keegan_1997_35_65-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFKeegan1997">Keegan 1997</a>, p.&#160;35.<br />
<a href="#CITEREFCienciala2010">Cienciala 2010</a>, p.&#160;128, observes that, while it is true that Poland was far away, making it difficult for the French and British to provide support, "[f]ew Western historians of World War II&#160;... know that the British had committed to bomb Germany if it attacked Poland, but did not do so except for one raid on the base of Wilhelmshafen. The French, who committed to attack Germany in the west, had no intention of doing so."</span></li>
